 @neonfrootbeach  i would agree with you if not for the fact that ive seen the overstimulating shit that 5 year olds watch four hours at a time and they completely lack any and all narrative or any kind of humor with thought put into it, nor any kind of learning material and very minimal content actually relevant with real world topics.

they're content farms that people put minimal effort in and they just throw flashy colors and characters in it and fart jokes and slime and kids get hooked, its a constant stream of stimulation with absolutely nothing being learned because you cant extract any kind of useful information from them to any degree. i've seen some of the long term effects and it makes kids very reliant on this type of media and hinders development because of how utterly empty the content is and being engaged in actually learning doesnt provide enough of the instant dopamine hit. it's gotten to the point where kids become completely dysfunctional without it.

it's one thing to be obsessed with generational culture and its another thing to feel concerned about how people are making content for kids that has so little effort put into it but takes up so much of the current internet space to make as much money as possible by just overstimulating kids. youtube poops in their conception had no profit incentive and even still they are made by very passionate people who put effort into actually making real jokes. maybe it's not exactly a proper alternative to show to kids compared to say dora the explorer or something, but its absolutely not comparable to the aforementioned algorithm slop out there, at least your kid would learn a sense of humor, or become familiar with real world topics.

